            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I second this request. Actually, I was looking around to see if I **could just disable the update check**. I update `pynvim` relatively infrequently, but still more frequently than `nvim`, which I do not manage myself.\n\nAs it currently stands, the healthcheck fails if the network is unavailable, even though `pynvim` works fine. I think the healthcheck should only display a warning if it cannot be performed, but not error out if `pynvim` is working:\n\n>```\n> Python 3 provider (optional) ~\n> - Using: g:python3_host_prog = \"/some/venv/bin/python\"\n> - Executable: /some/venv/bin/python\n> - Python version: 3.12.2\n> - pynvim version: 0.5.2\n> - WARNING Could not contact PyPI to get latest version.\n> - ERROR HTTP request failed: error: curl error with https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pynvim/json: 6\n> ```\n\n```Console\n$ curl --verbose -fL https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pynvim/json\n* Could not resolve host: pypi.python.org\n* Closing connection 0\ncurl: (6) Could not resolve host: pypi.python.org\n```\n\nSee also https://github.com/neovim/pynvim/issues/557\n\nAs a user, I also feel uncomfortable knowing that my text editor tries to access online services. It is typically the kind of application I would sandbox away from network access (except in a few specific cases: plugins, ssh edition, etc), so I was surprised to find this feature enabled by default.",
